[1]
Date: 28 Oct 2015
Source: Western Daily Press [edited]
http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Breaking-2nd-cow-dies-Westbury-anthrax-farm/story-28072104-detail/story.html


A 2nd cow is to be incinerated on the Westbury farm where anthrax was detected, government officials have confirmed. The cow is not strictly confirmed as carrying the deadly disease, and the authorities will wait for test results to confirm, but they said the development was "not unexpected."

Last Friday, a cow tested positive for anthrax and was incinerated on the farm, which is to the west of Westbury in Wiltshire, and a 2nd case has not caused an increase in the warnings to public health. The case, at Storridge Farm, caused the farm to be placed in movement restrictions and a mile-long footpath along the western edge of Westbury was closed off to the public to minimise the risk.

Farmers and farm workers on the site that came into contact with the herd are being monitored.

It is understood the farm is the site of an anthrax case in 1996, which was linked at the time with a former leather works nearby.

A spokesman for the Animal and Plant Health Agency said the case was not a surprise. "It is in the same farm, with the same herd from the same pasture, so it is not unexpected. The movement restrictions on the farm and for the public around remain in place, and our work there will continue to test the rest of the herd," he said.

"A 2nd cow has died at the farm, and tests are still being carried out. This development is not unexpected. The cow will be incinerated, and movement will continue to be restricted at the farm as we continue to follow the necessary procedures for dealing with this incident.

"We continue to work with our colleagues from Defra, Environment Agency and Wiltshire Council to investigate this case and closely monitor the welfare of the animals. Movement restrictions remain in place on the farm. The risk of infection in close human contacts of the animal is very low, and we continue to work with PHE to monitor potential human contacts."

[Byline: Tristan Cork]

