[Local gossip, for what it is worth, is as follows:

"Date: 27 Oct 2015
Source: Westbury Town Forum [edited]
http://www.westburytownforums.co.uk/index.php?topic=4745.0

Re: Anthrax Case near Westbury
-----------------------
It involves land which is some way away from the main residential parts of the town, which has now been sealed off from the public, but to stop people/the press inundating the farm with visits (which would be the opposite of what is needed) precise location information is not being circulated. The location is nowhere near the former old tannery site by Leigh Park/Westbury Leigh/ Dilton Marsh, which has an old history involving anthrax that is now buried below secure layers of fabric and additional topsoil, etc. Apparently, badgers have recently dug up the soil in the relevant field, and experts believe that this is the source. The field had a very small number of cattle in it."

For what it may be worth, until we have access to a more rigorous investigation. Dredging and mechanically clearing of contaminated stream or river beds is well recognised as a risk when one is either downstream of a tannery or where infected carcasses had lain. As tanneries routinely used contaminated hides, both domestic and imported, they have long been recognised as a potential source for anthrax outbreaks in livestock, whether in the UK, USA, Canada, India, today, wherever. How the badgers come into this is presently unclear.

For a satellite image of the village and Biss Brook, go to: http://www.wiltshiretimes.co.uk/news/13898243.UPDATE__Footpath_closed_after_case_of_anthrax_in_cow_confirmed_at_Westbury_farm/. - Mod.MHJ

